    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-08-24T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-08-24T11:00:00-05:00" n="48"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d48">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">894.24/1536: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Colombia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Braden</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bogotá</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-08-24T11:00:00-05:00"
                            >August 24, 1941—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 1:49 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>369. For Finletter. My telegram No. 365.<note n="68" xml:id="d48fn68">August 22,
                        4 p.m., not printed.</note> Yesterday afternoon I emphasized to President
                    Santos that it was imperative no platinum go to Japan or other totalitarian
                    country. He replied, “As you know that has been arranged. What about the silk?”
                    He then expressed deep regret for the matter having been taken up with me on
                        Friday<note n="69" xml:id="d48fn69">August 22.</note> both the Foreign
                    Minister and myself. I reassured him on this and repeated the hope already
                    stated to the Minister for Foreign Affairs that the Colombian Government would,
                    in view of the military requirements in the United States, withdraw its request
                    in this particular. He said since failure to get silk would ruin mill and put
                    284 employees out of work he preferred not to commit himself but leaves the
                    matter to be worked out between the Foreign Minister and myself.</p>
                <p>The Foreign Minister told me on 22d that the Japanese would accept nothing in
                    exchange for silk but platinum, not even gold metal.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Braden</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
